From: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
Date: Sun, 05 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: ethernet: qualcomm: ppe: offload PPPoE flows

Offload flows of a PPPoE WAN. The PPPOE_PUSH action of a rule maps to
a refcounted session slot of (egress port, session ID), which owns an
L3 interface past the per-port ones and a PPPoE session table entry.
The L3 interface carries the source MAC rewrite of the rule together
with the session ID and the PPPoE flag, so the hardware encapsulates
on egress; the session table entry assigns PPPoE ingress of the
session on that port to the same interface, which terminates it. The
reverse direction of the connection arrives as a plain rule of the
inner tuple - netfilter emits no decap key or action - and installs an
ordinary flow entry, which the terminated packets then hit. The
session table write bounds its index against the per-SoC table depth
carried by the variant.

The session entries match any server MAC, and multicast within a
session stays on the software path. The port L3 interface binding is
left untouched by PPPoE flows: session traffic resolves its interface
through the session table, and non-PPPoE ingress on a PPPoE WAN port
keeps taking the software path.

Also reject rules with match keys outside the supported set instead
of skipping the unknown keys. Tunnel routes, for example, arrive with
ENC_* keys, and offloading them as plain routed flows would have
transmitted the packets unencapsulated. The TCP flags key remains a
deliberate exception: the hardware forwards FIN/RST packets instead
of punting them, which only delays the flow teardown until the flow
idles out.

Signed-off-by: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/ppe_flow.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/ppe_flow.c
@@ -269,14 +269,19 @@ int ppe_my_mac_set(struct ppe_device *pp
  * @addr: MAC address of the interface, the source MAC of routed packets
  * leaving through it
  * @mtu: MTU of the interface
+ * @pppoe_sid: PPPoE session ID of the interface, negative when it is
+ * not a PPPoE interface
  *
  * Configure the ingress side (routing enable, MTU) and the egress side
- * (source MAC rewrite) of an L3 interface.
+ * (source MAC rewrite) of an L3 interface. On a PPPoE interface the
+ * ingress side terminates the session of the packets which the PPPoE
+ * session table assigned to the interface, and the egress side
+ * encapsulates the packets it transmits with the session ID.
  *
  * Return: 0 on success, negative error code on failure.
  */
 int ppe_l3_if_set(struct ppe_device *ppe_dev, int index, const u8 *addr,
-		  int mtu)
+		  int mtu, int pppoe_sid)
 {
 	u32 in[4] = {}, eg[4] = {};
 	u32 reg;
@@ -292,6 +297,9 @@ int ppe_l3_if_set(struct ppe_device *ppe
 	in[1] |= FIELD_PREP(PPE_IN_L3_IF_W1_MRU_IPV6, mtu);
 	in[2] = FIELD_PREP(PPE_IN_L3_IF_W2_MTU_IPV6, mtu);
 
+	if (pppoe_sid >= 0)
+		in[1] |= PPE_IN_L3_IF_W1_PPPOE_EN;
+
 	reg = PPE_IN_L3_IF_TBL_ADDR + PPE_IN_L3_IF_TBL_INC * index;
 	ret = regmap_bulk_write(ppe_dev->regmap, reg, in, ARRAY_SIZE(in));
 	if (ret)
@@ -301,12 +309,69 @@ int ppe_l3_if_set(struct ppe_device *ppe
 	eg[1] = FIELD_PREP(PPE_EG_L3_IF_W1_MAC_ADDR_HI,
 			   addr[0] << 8 | addr[1]);
 
+	if (pppoe_sid >= 0) {
+		eg[1] |= FIELD_PREP(PPE_EG_L3_IF_W1_SESSION_ID, pppoe_sid);
+		eg[2] = PPE_EG_L3_IF_W2_PPPOE_EN;
+	}
+
 	reg = PPE_EG_L3_IF_TBL_ADDR + PPE_EG_L3_IF_TBL_INC * index;
 
 	return regmap_bulk_write(ppe_dev->regmap, reg, eg, ARRAY_SIZE(eg));
 }
 
 /**
+ * ppe_pppoe_session_set - Program a PPPoE session table entry
+ * @ppe_dev: PPE device
+ * @index: PPPoE session table index
+ * @port: Ingress PPE port carrying the session, negative to clear the
+ * entry
+ * @sid: PPPoE session ID
+ * @l3_if: L3 interface assigned to the terminated packets
+ *
+ * Unicast packets of the session received on the port are assigned to
+ * the L3 interface, which terminates the session when its PPPoE flag
+ * is set. The entry matches any server MAC, and multicast within the
+ * session stays on the software path.
+ *
+ * Return: 0 on success, negative error code on failure.
+ */
+int ppe_pppoe_session_set(struct ppe_device *ppe_dev, int index, int port,
+			  u16 sid, int l3_if)
+{
+	u32 val, ext = 0, ext2 = 0;
+	int ret;
+
+	if (index >= ppe_dev->variant->num_pppoe_sessions)
+		return -EINVAL;
+
+	val = FIELD_PREP(PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_SESSION_ID, sid);
+	val |= FIELD_PREP(PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_PORT_BITMAP,
+			  port >= 0 ? BIT(port) : 0);
+
+	ret = regmap_write(ppe_dev->regmap,
+			   PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_ADDR +
+			   PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_INC * index, val);
+	if (ret)
+		return ret;
+
+	if (port >= 0) {
+		ext = PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_EXT_UC_VALID;
+		ext2 = PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_EXT2_L3_IF_VALID;
+		ext2 |= FIELD_PREP(PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_EXT2_L3_IF, l3_if);
+	}
+
+	ret = regmap_write(ppe_dev->regmap,
+			   PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_EXT_ADDR +
+			   PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_EXT_INC * index, ext);
+	if (ret)
+		return ret;
+
+	return regmap_write(ppe_dev->regmap,
+			    PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_EXT2_ADDR +
+			    PPE_PPPOE_SESSION_EXT2_INC * index, ext2);
+}
+
